04650nam a22008655i 9780814772980DE-B159720200723103303.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||200723t20092009nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808147729807 a10.18574/97808147729802doi  a(DE-B1597)547259  a(OCoLC)503553779  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 4aB105 .B64 C36 2009 7aSOC0020002bisacsh04a306.4a306.46131 aCasper, Monica J., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aMissing Bodies :bThe Politics of Visibility /cMonica J. Casper, Lisa Jean Moore. 1aNew York, NY : bNew York University Press, c[2009] 4cÂ©2009  a1 online resource  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aBiopolitics ;v200tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- t1. Introduction -- t2. Seen but Not Heard -- t3. Calculated Losses -- t4. Biodisaster -- t5. Fluid Matters -- t6. "They Used Me" -- t7. It Takes Balls -- t8. Conclusion -- tNotes -- tReferences -- tIndex -- tAbout the Authors 0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aWe know more about the physical body-how it begins, how it responds to illness, even how it decomposes-than ever before. Yet not all bodies are created equal, some bodies clearly count more than others, and some bodies are not recognized at all. In Missing Bodies, Monica J. Casper and Lisa Jean Moore explore the surveillance, manipulations, erasures, and visibility of the body in the twenty-first century. The authors examine bodies, both actual and symbolic, in a variety of arenas: pornography, fashion, sports, medicine, photography, cinema, sex work, labor, migration, medical tourism, and war. This new politicsof visibility can lead to the overexposure of some bodies-Lance Armstrong, Jessica Lynch-and to the near invisibility of others-dead Iraqi civilians, illegal immigrants, the victims of HIV/AIDS and "natural" disasters.Missing Bodies presents a call for a new, engaged way of seeing and recovering bodies in a world that routinely, often strategically,obscures or erases them. It poses difficult, even startling questions: Why did it take so long for the United States media to begin telling stories about the "falling bodies" of 9/11? Why has the United States government refused to allow photographs or filming of flag-draped coffins carrying the bodies of soldiers who are dying in Iraq? Why are the bodies of girls and women so relentlessly sexualized? By examining the cultural politics at work in such disappearances and inclusions of the physical body the authors show how the social, medical and economic consequences of visibility can reward or undermine privilege in society.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 23. Jul 2020) 0aBody image. 0aEquality. 0aHuman body (Philosophy) 0aMasculinity. 0aMortality. 4aCasper. 4aJean. 4aLisa. 4aMonica. 4aMoore. 4abody. 4acentury. 4aerasures. 4aexplore. 4amanipulations. 4asurveillance. 4atwenty-first. 4avisibility. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / General.2bisacsh1 aMoore, Lisa Jean, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertNYUP Backlist 2000-2013z978311070644440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780814772980423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780814772980.jpg  a978-3-11-070644-4  NYUP Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK